export const story = {"seriesId":"history-close-up","storyId":"russian-october-revolution","storyKey":"history-close-up/russian-october-revolution","seriesTitle":"History Close-Up","seriesDescription":"Narrative nonfiction for curious readers: real people, real turning points, and the choices that changed the world.","title":"Russian October Revolution","author":"Roughdraft Stories","description":"A factual story of the Bolshevik seizure of power in Petrograd and the collapse of the Provisional Government in 1917.","ageRange":"10-14","genre":"Narrative History","tags":["russian revolution","october revolution","lenin","trotsky","petrograd","1917"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"Russia on the Edge","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# Chapter 1: Russia on the Edge\n\nThe Russian October Revolution is usually remembered for its most dramatic moment, but the story began earlier. Historians usually date the event to October 24 to 25, 1917 on the Julian calendar; November 6 to 7, 1917 on the Gregorian calendar. It unfolded in Petrograd, Russia, especially the Winter Palace and key transport and communications points. By the time it reached the point most readers remember, pressure had already been building through fear, planning, rivalry, miscalculation, or stubborn political will.\n\nAmong the central figures were Vladimir Lenin, Leon Trotsky, Alexander Kerensky, Bolshevik Red Guards, soldiers and sailors in Petrograd. Provisional Government loses authority amid war, shortages, and political radicalization. Bolsheviks gain influence in soviets and military committees.\n\nWhat made the buildup dangerous was the size of the stakes. Destruction of the fragile post-tsar political order. Beginning of Bolshevik rule and the path toward civil war and Soviet state formation.\n\nAnyone watching closely before the decisive turn would have noticed armed workers and soldiers taking city nodes at night, smolny Institute buzzing as a revolutionary headquarters, and winter Palace entered amid confusion more than cinematic grandeur. Those details matter because they show the world before the break, when the outcome was still uncertain but the crisis was already hardening into something larger.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"The Seizure of Petrograd","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# Chapter 2: The Seizure of Petrograd\n\n**PETROGRAD, November 7, 1917**  \nBolshevik forces have seized key points across Petrograd and overthrown the Provisional Government, bringing Russia's long year of revolution to a new and decisive break. On the New Style calendar the date is November 7, though the event is still widely known as the October Revolution because it occurred on October 25 by the old Russian calendar. Bridges, railway stations, telegraph points, and government buildings were occupied in quick succession. By the time many residents understood what was happening, the capital's essential machinery was already passing into new hands.\n\nThe Winter Palace, though later generations may remember it as the center of one dramatic assault, fell after confusion, pressure, and weakening resistance rather than one clean theatrical moment. What matters more is that the Bolsheviks, led politically by Lenin and organized militarily in large part by Trotsky and allied soviet forces, have claimed power in the name of workers' and soldiers' councils.\n\nRussia now enters an even more uncertain phase. War, hunger, land hunger, desertion, and state collapse made this seizure possible. They will also shape what comes next. The fall of one government does not end the revolution. It may only begin its most dangerous chapter.\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"How October Changed the Century","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# Chapter 3: How October Changed the Century\n\nThe event did not end when the most famous scene was over. Armed detachments seize bridges, telegraph stations, and rail points. Winter Palace falls and the Provisional Government collapses. Bolsheviks proclaim transfer of power to the soviets.\n\nResearchers still handle the details carefully. They often re-check how \"bloodless\" Petrograd was depends on whether one isolates the capital seizure from ensuing violence elsewhere and popular support levels are contested. Historians usually agree on the broad shape of the event while still debating totals, categories, or which figures best describe what happened.\n\nMemory also shapes this story. \"Storming of the Winter Palace\" was later mythologized in Soviet art and film. Calendar issue must be explained clearly for young readers. Keep both dates visible when needed: October 25 Old Style and November 7 New Style.\n\nThe Russian October Revolution mattered because it changed more than the people who stood closest to it. Destruction of the fragile post-tsar political order. Beginning of Bolshevik rule and the path toward civil war and Soviet state formation. That is why the event remains worth studying long after the original fear, smoke, or confusion have passed.\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":3,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
